  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is quartz or granite better for Seattle kitchens?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Quartz is generally the better choice for Seattle kitchens due to its non-porous surface, zero-maintenance properties, and superior stain resistance. In Seattle\'s moisture-heavy climate, quartz\'s resistance to mold and bacteria growth is a significant advantage over granite, which requires annual sealing to prevent moisture absorption.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is quartz more expensive than granite in Seattle?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Quartz and granite have overlapping price ranges. Granite costs $40-$100 per square foot installed in Seattle, while quartz runs $50-$120 per square foot. Entry-level granite is cheaper than entry-level quartz, but mid-range options are comparable. When you factor in the lifetime cost of annual sealing for granite ($100-$200 per year), quartz often has a lower total cost of ownership.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Which countertop has better resale value in Seattle?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Both quartz and granite are considered premium countertop materials that appeal to Seattle buyers. However, quartz has surpassed granite as the most in-demand countertop material in the Puget Sound real estate market. Quartz countertops are a strong selling point that signals a modern, updated kitchen to potential buyers.' },
    },
